What is git tag? (Super Simple Explanation)

A git tag is like putting a bookmark or label on a specific commit.

You use it when you want to mark an important point in your project, such as:

A release: v1.0.0

A milestone: beta-1

A production deployment: prod-2025-11-27

Tags NEVER move.
They always stick to the SAME commit â€” unlike branches, which keep moving.

ğŸ¯ Why do we use git tags?

Because they help you:

âœ” Mark releases
git tag v1.0.0

âœ” Go back to a stable version anytime
git checkout v1.0.0

âœ” Deploy a specific version in CI/CD
git checkout tags/v2.3.1

âœ” Compare versions
git diff v1.0.0 v2.0.0

ğŸ§  Types of Tags
1ï¸âƒ£ Lightweight Tag (simple bookmark)

Just a label, no metadata.

git tag v1.0.0

2ï¸âƒ£ Annotated Tag (recommended)

Contains:

Tag message

Tagger name

Email

Timestamp

git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "First stable release"

ğŸ”§ Useful Git Tag Commands
ğŸ‘‰ List all tags
git tag

ğŸ‘‰ Create annotated tag
git tag -a v2.0 -m "Release version 2.0"

ğŸ‘‰ Tag a specific commit
git tag -a v2.1 3c9e1d4 -m "Hotfix"

ğŸ‘‰ Push tags to GitHub
git push origin --tags

ğŸ‘‰ Push a single tag
git push origin v1.0.0

ğŸ‘‰ Delete a local tag
git tag -d v1.0.0

ğŸ‘‰ Delete a remote tag
git push origin :refs/tags/v1.0.0

ğŸ§¨ Real-Life Example (You will use this a lot)
You finished a release and want to mark it:
git tag -a v3.5.1 -m "Production release"
git push origin v3.5.1


Your CI/CD pipeline can now deploy v3.5.1.

If Prod crashes due to new changes?
Just roll back:

git checkout v3.5.1

