Letâ€™s break it down cleanly ğŸ‘‡

âœ… Two Ways to Create Tags
1ï¸âƒ£ Lightweight Tag (NOT recommended for releases)

Just a name pointing to a commit.
git tag v1.0


âŒ No message
âŒ No metadata
âŒ Not good for release history
âŒ Not used in real projects

2ï¸âƒ£ Annotated Tag (RECOMMENDED for all real use)
This stores:

âœ” Tag message
âœ” Author name
âœ” Email
âœ” Timestamp
âœ” The commit it points to

To create it:
git tag -a v1.0 -m "Production release version 1.0"

Or without quotes:
git tag -a v1.0

Git will open an editor to type message.

ğŸš€ So what should YOU use?
ğŸ‘‰ Always use annotated tags:
